> Configuring Git 
-- To configure the name git will associate your work with
   git config --global user.name "<username>"
-- To check -> git config user.name
-- To configure the email git will associate your work with 
   git config --global user.email "<user email>"
-- To check -> git config user.email 
-- We can see all your Git settings with -> git config --list
-- To remove a setting -> git config --global --unset <user. email> 
-- Set the default branch name for new repositories (for example, main instead of master) -> git config --global init.defaultBranch main

-- There are three levels of configuration:
    System (all users): git config --system
    Global (current user): git config --global
    Local (current repo): git config --local


> What is GIT REPOSITORY?
-- It is a workplace which tracks and manages files within a folder. 
   If we want to create a new project. app etc, we have to create a new git repo. We can have as many repos on our machine as needed with separate histories and contents. 
   Two types of repositories are there - 
   Public repository - it will be visible by everyone

   private repository - it will not be visible for everyone.

> COMMANDS -
-- 1> Git status -> gives current status of the git repo and it's contents.
                    [git status]
-- 2> Git init -> To create a new git repo. Before, we can do anything git related we must initialize our repo first. Make sure you are not inside a repo while executing this command.
                  Git creates a hidden folder called .git inside your project.    
                  [git init]
-- 3> Commit -> commit everything that was previously added and staged.  
                [ Commit workflow - work on stuff > add changes > commit]
                [git commit -m "message"]
-- 4> Git add -> we use git add command to stage changes to be committed. 
                 [ git add <file name> - add that particular file ]
                 [ git add . - adds all the files ]
-- 5> Git Log -> It logs all the commits of given repo. 
                 [ git log] 








  

  




